text: In the cross-asset sense, so if I'm in future space and I'm looking at a bunch of equity index futures, we don't find a lot of predictive power in being long a set that has done better recently and short a set that's done worse recently. Once we're adjusting for riskiness, right? Russell 2000 is going to be a little riskier than S&P. And so when we operate and we build portfolios, we're usually thinking about stuff in risk-adjusted space. And once you're risk-adjusting, the predictive power, the relative performance seems to go away. Why would that be? Well, it's that predictive power. So let's say Russell 2000 has a higher beta to equities in general than S&P. When beta is working, if you're not risk-adjusting, Russell 2000 will be doing better. And when beta is not working, it'll be doing worse. That's the idea. Once you risk-adjust, there's really no – we don't find any persistent predictive power in relative performance within related assets. So I think a lot of the equity research as well is probably not risk-adjusted. So that it is a bit… I think it's a bit of a beta timing phenomenon that you're seeing in equity momentum. Stocks that have done well recently or on a relative basis are the ones that have been – had the right over- or under-exposure to beta in some cases, or to the right industry, or whatever it is. Well, in multi-asset space, momentum is good. It might work pretty well if you're just capturing relative beta exposures. But once you're adjusting for that and putting everything on the sand, like a level playing field, that predictive power of the sort goes away. And all you're left with is the time series.
